# espeak-ng dictionary source for chemistry/biology pronunciation
#
# AS OF v0.15.0 THIS FILE IS LIVE: entries below are compiled into a custom
# en_dict (~170 KB) at content/en_dict.chem. The plugin drops it into
# Piper's espeak-ng-data/ on dialog open. Engine-level pronunciation.
#
# Compile workflow (any Linux box with espeak-ng 1.51+):
#   1. mkdir build && cd build
#   2. curl upstream en_list, en_rules, en_emoji into ./
#   3. Inject these .replace pairs into en_rules' top .replace block
#      (just before `.group a`)
#   4. cp espeak-ng-data ./   (full data tree)
#   5. espeak-ng --path=. --compile=en
#   6. Output: ./espeak-ng-data/en_dict (binary)
#
# Format: lines under `.replace` are `source\ttarget` pairs. Each blank
# line ends the .replace block, so each section needs `.replace` redeclared.
# Comments must use `//` (not `#`) inside the en_rules file.
#
# ─── ESPEAK-NG COMPILER (step 2, plugin v0.14.3) ──────────────────────
#
# Latest release: 1.52.0  (https://github.com/espeak-ng/espeak-ng)
# Windows asset: espeak-ng.msi
#   https://github.com/espeak-ng/espeak-ng/releases/download/1.52.0/espeak-ng.msi
#
# Only an MSI installer ships (no portable zip). Either install it on the
# dev machine, or extract with `msiexec /a … /qb TARGETDIR=…` for a portable
# layout. Recommended plugin path: precompile a supplemental dict on a dev
# machine and bake the binary into the XPI — no runtime compile.
#
# ─── COMPILE FLOW (step 3, plugin v0.14.4) ────────────────────────────
#
# espeak-ng's en dictionary is built from these source files (all UTF-8):
#   en_list   — word→phonemes lookups (5794 lines upstream)
#   en_rules  — phoneme rule patterns
#   en_emoji  — emoji descriptions
# Source location: https://github.com/espeak-ng/espeak-ng/tree/master/dictsource
#
# Convention: do NOT modify en_list. Create a SIBLING file `en_extra` in
# the same dictsource/ directory with our additions. The compiler picks
# it up automatically. (en_list itself documents this on lines 1-2.)
#
# Format inside en_extra is identical to en_list:
#   word        phonemes        flags
# OR a `.replace` block (which we use in chem.list — text→text rewrites
# that get re-phonemized by the rules engine).
#
# Compile invocation, run from the dir containing en_list / en_extra etc.:
#   espeak-ng --path=<dictsource-parent> --compile=en
# Output: en_dict (binary) inside espeak-ng-data/.
#
# Next slices: (a) script the compile end-to-end on dev box, (b) inspect
# Piper's bundled espeak-ng-data layout to confirm the en_dict drop point,
# (c) run an A/B test ("IC50" before vs after).
#
# Upstream en dictsource (needed at compile time):
#   https://github.com/espeak-ng/espeak-ng/tree/master/dictsource

.replace
# Chiral / stereo descriptors
d.r.        d r
d.r         d r
e.e.        e e
e.e         e e
e.r.        e r
e.r         e r

